<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="1049" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1049">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.8273/84b.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister at Mexico
                                        City</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-06">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 6, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>113. Department would appreciate brief telegraphic statement of
                                charges which were lodged by Huerta Government against Vice Consul
                                Silliman, including information as to whether these charges have now
                                been dismissed. Would Silliman’s return to Saltillo at this time be
                                likely to embarrass you in any way?</p>
                            <p>As a matter of record, the Department would be glad to have copies by
                                mail of the notes exchanged by you with the Mexican Foreign Office
                                in regard to Silliman, if not objectionable to you.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>